<seg id=1> The United Nations Economic Commission for Latin America and the Caribbean Region estimates that economic growth in the region may decrease to one percent next year. </seg>
<seg id=2> However, this organization admits that the situation may be worse. </seg>
<seg id=3> Please listen now to a detailed report by Voice of America South American Department reporter Michael. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> Initial observation by the United Nations Economic Commission indicates that the economic growth rate in the Latin America and Caribbean Region will be 2.3 percent this year, which is a sharp drop from the 5.2 percent of last year. </seg>
<seg id=5> If the economy had not picked up sharply in the latter half of the year, the red ink this year might be much worse. </seg>
<seg id=6> The Commission says that despite external shocks, the economy of this region has performed quite well. </seg>
<seg id=7> However, the worst effects have now begun to manifest themselves and will continue through next year. </seg>
<seg id=8> The United Nations Economic Commission says that difficulty in the Brazilian economy is reflected in some of the countries in the southern cone region. </seg>
<seg id=9> Most of these countries have been affected by low prices for their main export products. </seg>
<seg id=10> The Commission says most countries have elected to raise interest rates to protect their currencies. </seg>
<seg id=11> Such measures inhibit economic growth and cause unemployment to rise. </seg>
